Date: 28/1/1908
Source: Nelson Evening Mail
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: First the nor'-wester, chased the flames for a mile or two;  then when the people began to breathe a little freely, the wind chopped round to sou'-west, and blew as only a "spout-wind" can, and drove the fire back again.
Notes:

Date: 24/6/1885
Source: Marlborough Express
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: When the first big fire occurred in Nelson in August, 1866, that town was in as helpless a state as Havelock is now. A "spout" wind was blowing, and eighteen houses were destroyed.
Notes:

Date: 16/9/1897
Source: Otago Witness
Author:
Vol / Page: 23
Edition:
Quote: Clothes fire-dried, and off next morning through miles of the Hope Saddle porridge, tons of rain, and overgrown cycles of keen spout wind.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1862
Source: Memories of NZ Life
Author: HODDER
Vol / Page: 46
Edition:
Quote: [The Waimea] is visited by a strong local wind, which blows with considerable violence, especially during the summer months. It is called the `spout wind', and is attributable to the peculiar configuration of the mountain ranges.
Notes:

Date: 14/2/1873
Source: Diary
Author: G.M. WILSON
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: (Nelson) There was a pretty strong wind blowing, what they call a `spout wind' from the fact of its coming down the valley on the town.
